RISKSIMTABLE allows a user to view a distribution of results rather than just one result.  This helps to compare items such as mean, standard deviation, etc.  These characteristics can help a company make the best possible decsion for their company.  They can decide based on the RISKSIMTABLE how risky they want their decision to be. 

An example of a simulation model and how RISKSIMTABLE is used, would be Walton Books.  Walton Books needed to know how many copies of books to make.  When all of their costs, and profits were entered into the model, they could then come up with simulations.  The simulation analysis requires the number of iterations to be put in.  Iterations are the number of outcomes that will be shown  on the RISKSIMTABLE.  My group had chosen the outcome with the highest mean profit, although that meant there was much more risk involved.  The standard deviation was higher, which showed that there was more of a chance of error.  But, we said, the greater the risk, the greater the possibility for reward. It was an advantage for the company to see all of the results next to each other, rather than single, individual results.  The comparisons were easier to make.
